metadata.name: Reconnaissance #257
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe theyâ€™re recon from another planetâ€™s civilization â€” one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium â€œThis is Mars,â€ Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands â€” and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for whatâ€™s next.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #54
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Valley Window #27
metadata.description:
Valley Window is inspired by the photograph "Monument Valley Window" by David Muench.
This valley is a little more other-worldly and the sand in the air creates some gorgeous colours as the sun sets / rises.  
The main interactive feature is the ability to change the position of the sun shader using the mouse - click to set the position and use space bar to release the sun to move it again. 
If you want to see the sunset without the foreground rocks they can be removed using the keys e,r,t and reinstated with d,f,g.
Enjoy!

metadata.name: Transmission #23
metadata.description:
GT by Ahmad Moussa || Gorilla Sun
Twitter -> @gorillasu

Notes on randomness and rarity:
This token generates a random permutation of a transmission. A transmission consists of a set of points (interceptors) that a diagonally spanned across the canvas, and connected with lines.
These interceptors can sometimes occur in a square shape.
Sometimes the signal fails to connect two dots, the amount of drops in these connections makes up the decomposition parameter.
The colored ligaments come in a variety of colors, and sometimes the entire transmission has a different color scheme. Some color schemes are extremely rare.

Notes on posting to Twitter:
To make Twitter display these correctly and not harshly compress them, they're best saved in the .jpg or .jpeg format and then posted.
Generative shapes and lines by petit sapin.

metadata.name: cLAZY MONSTER #21
metadata.description:
This project is Generative Layered PNGs files.

There are 11-Layers mixing together to make many unique 1/1 cLAZY MONSTER.

00-Background - 18 items
01-BackgroundComponent - 14 items
02-Body - 3 items
03-Clothes - 16 items
04-Face_Base - 1 item
05-Face_Level_1 - 20 items
06-Face_Level_2 - 21 items
07-Eyes - 14 items
08-Mouth - 7 items
09-Hands - 10 items
10-Nose - 11 items

So the maximum possibilities to be unique is
18x14x3x16x1x20x21x14x7x10x11 = 54,765,849,600 chances!

Good Luck, cLAZY MONSTER team!
